**Project StressWatch - AI-Enhanced Self-Monitoring System : Documentation Cum Guide**

---

# 1\. Create 3 New Clones:                                      

   \- Create virtual machines named:  
     \- vm0  
     \- vm1  
     \- vm2  
   \- Ensure the VMs run a compatible Linux distribution (CentOS 9 in our case).

1. Created three clones of centOS9  
2. Stopped firewall on all 3 servers → systemctl stop firewalld

# 2\. Ansible For Installation Of Software:

- Install Ansible on your local machine.  
- Establish a passwordless ssh connection between your local machine and the 3 VMs that you have created.  
- Use Ansible to automate the installation of required software on the VMs (Prometheus, Grafana, MySQL, exporters, etc.).  
- Create Ansible playbooks to ensure all configurations are consistent across the VMs.

Copy the content for hosts.ini file from (make obvious changes):  
[https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/hosts.ini](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/hosts.ini)

In playbook.yml you can copy the content from this file: [https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/playbook.yml](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/playbook.yml)

Then in the terminal, run:

\> ansible-playbook \-i hosts.ini playbook.yml


After the successful execution of the above codes, your VMs will have the following software:

- vm0 \- Prometheus, Grafana, Alertmanager  
- vm1 \- Jenkins, Docker, Node Exporter, Python, MySQL Exporter  
- vm2 \- MySQL Server

# 3\. Configuration & Setup

- Start services:   
  1\. Start grafana server in vm0  
  2\. Start Jenkins services and docker services in vm1  
  3\. Start MySQL server on vm2


- Setting Up MySQL server in vm2:  
1. Create a user and database with remote access allowed.

   `CREATE USER 'remote'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'YourStrongPassword';`

   `GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON *.* TO 'remote'@'%';` 

   `FLUSH PRIVILEGES;`

   `CREATE DATABASE stressTest;` 

   `GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON stressTest.* TO 'remote'@'%';` 

   `FLUSH PRIVILEGES;`

   

- Configuration In vm1:  
1. Create a .my.cnf file and populate it with:

   `[client]`

   `user=remote`

   `password=<YourStrongPassword>`

   `host=<vm2 IP>`

   `port=3306`

   

2. Give Jenkins users sudo privileges and switch to Jenkins user.

   

3. Set up passwordless ssh connection between jenkins@vm1 and root@vm2.

   

- Configuration in vm0  
1. Get inside Prometheus directory and create a myrules.yml file and populate with the content present in : 

   [https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/myrules.yml](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/myrules.yml)

   

2. Get into alertmanager directory and populate the with content present in:

   [https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/myrules.yml](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/myrules.yml)

   (Don't forget to make necessary changes)

# 5\. Image Creation And Kubernetes Deployment:

- Download Dockerfile from :   
  [https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/Dockerfile](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/Dockerfile)  
    
- To create an image run the command:  
  `> docker build -t <DockerhubUserName>/<imageName>:<tag>`  
    
- Login into the docker hub via command:  
  \> docker login  
    
- Push the newly created image on docker hub via the command:  
  `> docker push <DockerhubUserName>/<imageName>:<tag>`


  
![][image2]

- (Install minikube and kubectl in vm1 and start minikube)  
    
- For Kubernetes deployment create a use:  
  [https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/deployment.yaml](https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400/blob/main/deployment.yaml)  
    
- In deployment.yaml file change:  
  `image: codegotham/pystresstest:v1`  
                  to  
  `image: <DockerhubUserName>/<imageName>:<tag>`

- To generate K8s secret file to use info stored in .env use this command  
  `> kubectl create secrete generic env --from-file=.env`  
    
- To create deployments run the command:  
  `> kubeclt apply -f deployment.yaml`  
    
- Check  K8s dashboard:  
  `> minikube dashboard`

# 6\. Version Control and CI/CD:

- Switch to vm1 and switch to Jenkins browser dashboard.  
    
- Generate a publicly accessible link for Jenkins via ngrok.  
    
- Create a GitHub repository and create a webhook that gets triggered to make a new Jenkins build when there’s a new push in the repo (use the link produced by ngrok here to create a webhook)  
    
- Code for Jenkins pipeline:  
  `pipeline {`  
      `agent any`  
      `stages {`  
          `stage('Cloning') {`  
              `steps {`  
                  `git branch: 'main', url: 'https://github.com/GothamKnight17/MajorProjectC400.git'`  
              `}`  
          `}`  
          `stage('Copying to VM2') {`  
              `steps {`  
                  `sh """`  
                      `scp -r -i /var/lib/jenkins/myKey /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/MajorProject/ root@192.168.1.22:/root`  
                  `"""`  
              `}`  
          `}`  
          `stage('Verifying Presence Of Updated Code In VM2') {`   
              `steps {`   
                  `sh """`  
                      `ssh -i /var/lib/jenkins/myKey root@192.168.1.22 <<EOF`  
  `if [ -d "/root/MajorProject" ]; then`   
      `echo "Directory exists and contains the following files:"`  
      `ls /root/MajorProject`  
  `else`  
      `echo "Directory does not exist."`  
  `fi`  
  `EOF`  
                  `"""`  
              `}`  
          `}`  
      `}`  
  `}`

- Pushing changes in the repo will trigger the webhook initialising the new Jenkins build and the latest update will get pushed to vm2 automatically and it will also verify successful transfer.
